Based on the article, here are some examples of Claude Code hooks for automating Git commits:

1. Basic Commit on Session Completion
The article demonstrates a simple hook that automatically commits changes when a Claude Code session ends:

```json
{
  "hooks": {
    "Stop": [
      {
        "matcher": "",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "/path/to/post_chat.rb"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

2. Multi-Branch Session Tracking
A more advanced approach creates separate branches for parallel coding sessions:

```json
{
  "hooks": {
    "PreToolUse": [
      {
        "matcher": "Edit|MultiEdit|Write",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "~/bin/pre_tool_call.rb"
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "PostToolUse": [
      {
        "matcher": "Edit|MultiEdit|Write",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "~/bin/post_tool_call.rb"
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "Stop": [
      {
        "matcher": "",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "~/bin/stop_call.rb"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

Key features of these hooks include:
- Automatically committing changes after session completion
- Creating separate branches for different coding sessions
- Using session-specific commit messages
- Tracking changes across parallel coding tasks

The article suggests these are "powerful tool[s] for automating your agent workflows" with Claude Code.

